{"title_page": "Jill Evans", "text_new": "{{short description|British politician and MEP}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name             = Jill Evans\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = Evans, Jill-1665.jpg\n| office           = [[Member of the European Parliament]] <br> for [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]]\n| term_start       = 10 June 1999\n| term_end         = 31 January 2020\n| parliament       = European\n| predecessor      = ''Constituency established''\n| successor        = ''Constituency abolished''\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1959|5|8|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Ystrad]], [[Rhondda]], [[Wales]]\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = [[Welsh people|Welsh]]\n| spouse           = [[Syd Morgan]]\n| relations        =\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Wales, Aberystwyth]]<br>[[Glamorgan University]] (now the [[University of South Wales]])\n| occupation       = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n| party            = '''''{{flag|Wales|name=Welsh}}'''''<br>[[Plaid Cymru]]<br>'''''{{flag|EU}}'''''<br>[[European Free Alliance]]\n| website          = http://www.jillevans.net/\n}}\n[[File:Evans, Jill (en).webm|thumb|Video Introduction '''(English)''' / [[:File:Evans, Jill (cy).webm|(Welsh)]]]]\n\n'''Jill Evans''' (born 8 May 1959) is [[Plaid Cymru]] politician who served as a [[Member of the European Parliament]] for [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]] from 1999 to 2020.<ref name=\"euro_Jill\">{{Cite web\n| title = Jill EVANS| work = europarl.europa.eu| url = http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/4550/JILL_EVANS_history.html}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1999, Evans was elected as the MEP for Plaid Cymru,<ref name=\"jill_Speech\">{{Cite web| title = Plaid Cymru Annual Conference Speech, Aberystwyth| work = Jill Evans MEP| date = 12 October 2013| url = http://www.jillevans.net/english/jill_evans_speeches_plaid_cymru_conference_aberystwyth_131012.html}}</ref> and was subsequently reelected every five years ever since. From 2009 until 2014, she was the Vice-President of the Greens/[[European Free Alliance]] Group, and is a member of the Committee on Culture and Education.<ref name=\"euro_Jill\" />\n\nShe also deputises on the Transport and Tourism Committee and is a member of the Delegation for relations with Switzerland and Norway and to the EU-Iceland Joint Parliamentary Committee and the European Economic Area (EEA) Joint Parliamentary Committee.\n\n==Background==\nEvans was born in [[Ystrad]], [[Rhondda]].  She was educated at Tonypandy Grammar School<ref name=\"wale_Jill\">{{Cite web| title = Jill campaigns for famous fountain| work = WalesOnline| date = 17 August 2006| url = https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/local-news/jill-campaigns-for-famous-fountain-2321907}}</ref> before attending the Polytechnic of Wales, Trefforest (now [[University of South Wales]]) where she earned an M.Phil.\n\n==Professional career==\nEvans worked as a Research Assistant at the former [[Polytechnic of Wales]]. She later worked as public affairs officer for the [[National Federation of Women's Institutes]] in Wales for six years. Following her first election to public office, she took up the post of Wales Organiser for CHILD - the infertility support network.<ref name=\"jill_Jill\">{{Cite web| title = About Me| author = Jill Evans MEP| url = http://www.jillevans.net/english/jill_evans_biography.html}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nEvans was a [[political activist]] before being elected to [[public office]], and participated in the [[Greenham Common]] campaign.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Greenham women mark missile fight| work = BBC News| date = 27 August 2001| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/1510570.stm}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/897040520 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/896554291 cite #5 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> She first stood in [[Torfaen (UK Parliament constituency)|Torfaen]] in the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|General Election of 1987]]. She was later elected to Rhondda Borough Council in 1992, [[Mid Glamorgan County Council]] in 1993, and, following the abolition of these, to the Rhondda Cynon Taf Council in 1995, standing down in 1999.\n\nDuring her time as a councillor, she was elected as Plaid Cymru's Alternate Member of the Committee of the Regions in 1993 and served for four years, and was also the party's representative on the European Free Alliance, working with Plaid Cymru's sister parties throughout the continent.\n\nJill was Chair of Plaid Cymru between 1994 and 1996. In June 1999 she was elected as a Member of the European Parliament for Wales, becoming the Party\u2019s first MEP. Evans was re-elected at subsequent elections in 2004, 2009, 2014 and 2019.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Jill EVANS| work = europarl.europa.eu| url = http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/4550/JILL_EVANS_history.html}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/897040520 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/896554291 cite #1 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2009 \u2013 2014 Parliament, Evans was a member of the Green / European Free Alliance (EFA) Group - the fourth largest group in the Parliament. She was the President of EFA, and the first Vice-President of the Greens/EFA Group in the European Parliament. Jill also deputised on the Delegation for Relations with the Palestine Legislative Council.\n\nShe was a member of the Committee on the Environment, Public Health and Food Safety and the Delegation for relations with Iraq. She deputised on the Agriculture Committee.\n\nIn the parliament (2014 - 2019), Jill was the Vice-President of the EFA Group, and a member of the Committee on Culture and Education. She deputised on the Transport and Tourism Committee. She was also a member of the Delegation for relations with Switzerland and Norway and to the EU-Iceland Joint Parliamentary Committee and the European Economic Area (EEA) Joint Parliamentary Committee.\n\nJill is former President of Plaid Cymru, and the current Chair of CND Cymru.\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|eu}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of European Parliament]] for [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]]\n  | years  = [[1999 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|1999]]\u2013 2020\n}}\n{{s-non  | reason  = Constituency abolished }}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box | title = Chair of [[Plaid Cymru]] | years = 1994\u20131996 | before = [[John Dixon (Welsh politician)|John Dixon]] | after = [[Marc Phillips]] }}\n{{succession box| title=Vice President of [[Plaid Cymru]] | years=2004\u20132010 | before=[[Dafydd Iwan]] | after=[[Chris Franks]]}}\n{{s-bef  | before = [[Dafydd Iwan]]}}\n{{S-ttl\n  | title  = President of [[Plaid Cymru]]\n  | years  = 2010\u20132013\n}}\n{{s-non|reason  = Position abolished}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Plaid Cymru}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evans, Jill}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Aberystwyth University]]\n[[Category:People from Ystrad]]\n[[Category:Plaid Cymru councillors]]\n[[Category:Plaid Cymru MEPs]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1999\u20132004]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2004\u20132009]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2009\u20132014]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2014\u20132019]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2019\u20132020]]\n[[Category:20th-century women MEPs for Wales]]\n[[Category:21st-century women MEPs for Wales]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of South Wales]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glamorgan]]\n[[Category:Welsh-speaking politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of Rhondda Cynon Taf County Borough Council]]\n[[Category:Plaid Cymru parliamentary candidates]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British politician and MEP}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name             = Jill Evans\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = Evans, Jill-1665.jpg\n| office           = [[Member of the European Parliament]] <br> for [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]]\n| term_start       = 10 June 1999\n| term_end         = 31 January 2020\n| parliament       = European\n| predecessor      = ''Constituency established''\n| successor        = ''Constituency abolished''\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1959|5|8|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Ystrad]], [[Rhondda]], [[Wales]]\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = [[Welsh people|Welsh]]\n| spouse           = [[Syd Morgan]]\n| relations        =\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Wales, Aberystwyth]]<br>[[Glamorgan University]] (now the [[University of South Wales]])\n| occupation       = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n| party            = '''''{{flag|Wales|name=Welsh}}'''''<br>[[Plaid Cymru]]<br>'''''{{flag|EU}}'''''<br>[[European Free Alliance]]\n| website          = http://www.jillevans.net/\n}}\n[[File:Evans, Jill (en).webm|thumb|Video Introduction '''(English)''' / [[:File:Evans, Jill (cy).webm|(Welsh)]]]]\n\n'''Jill Evans''' (born 8 May 1959) is [[Plaid Cymru]] politician who served as a [[Member of the European Parliament]] for [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]] from 1999 to 2020.<ref name=\"euro_Jill\">{{Cite web\n| title = Jill EVANS| work = europarl.europa.eu| url = http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/4550/JILL_EVANS_history.html}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1999, Evans was elected as the MEP for Plaid Cymru,<ref name=\"jill_Speech\">{{Cite web| title = Plaid Cymru Annual Conference Speech, Aberystwyth| work = Jill Evans MEP| date = 12 October 2013| url = http://www.jillevans.net/english/jill_evans_speeches_plaid_cymru_conference_aberystwyth_131012.html}}</ref> and was subsequently reelected every five years ever since. From 2009 until 2014, she was the Vice-President of the Greens/[[European Free Alliance]] Group, and is a member of the Committee on Culture and Education.<ref name=\"euro_Jill\" />\n\nShe also deputises on the Transport and Tourism Committee and is a member of the Delegation for relations with Switzerland and Norway and to the EU-Iceland Joint Parliamentary Committee and the European Economic Area (EEA) Joint Parliamentary Committee.\n\n==Background==\nEvans was born in [[Ystrad]], [[Rhondda]].  She was educated at Tonypandy Grammar School<ref name=\"wale_Jill\">{{Cite web| title = Jill campaigns for famous fountain| work = WalesOnline| date = 17 August 2006| url = https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/local-news/jill-campaigns-for-famous-fountain-2321907}}</ref> before attending the Polytechnic of Wales, Trefforest (now [[University of South Wales]]) where she earned an M.Phil.\n\n==Professional career==\nEvans worked as a Research Assistant at the former [[Polytechnic of Wales]]. She later worked as public affairs officer for the [[National Federation of Women's Institutes]] in Wales for six years. Following her first election to public office, she took up the post of Wales Organiser for CHILD - the infertility support network.<ref name=\"jill_Jill\">{{Cite web| title = About Me| author = Jill Evans MEP| url = http://www.jillevans.net/english/jill_evans_biography.html}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nEvans was a [[political activist]] before being elected to [[public office]], and participated in the [[Greenham Common]] campaign.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Greenham women mark missile fight| work = BBC News| date = 27 August 2001| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/1510570.stm}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/897040520 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/896554291 cite #5 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> She first stood in [[Torfaen (UK Parliament constituency)|Torfaen]] in the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|General Election of 1987]]. She was later elected to Rhondda Borough Council in 1992, [[Mid Glamorgan County Council]] in 1993, and, following the abolition of these, to the Rhondda Cynon Taf Council in 1995, standing down in 1999.\n\nDuring her time as a councillor, she was elected as Plaid Cymru's Alternate Member of the Committee of the Regions in 1993 and served for four years, and was also the party's representative on the European Free Alliance, working with Plaid Cymru's sister parties throughout the continent.\n\nJill was Chair of Plaid Cymru between 1994 and 1996. In June 1999 she was elected as a Member of the European Parliament for Wales, becoming the Party\u2019s first MEP. Evans was re-elected at subsequent elections in 2004, 2009, 2014 and 2019.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Jill EVANS| work = europarl.europa.eu| url = http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/4550/JILL_EVANS_history.html}} {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/897040520 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/896554291 cite #1 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2009 \u2013 2014 Parliament, Evans was a member of the Green / European Free Alliance (EFA) Group - the fourth largest group in the Parliament. She was the President of EFA, and the first Vice-President of the Greens/EFA Group in the European Parliament. Jill also deputised on the Delegation for Relations with the Palestine Legislative Council.\n\nShe was a member of the Committee on the Environment, Public Health and Food Safety and the Delegation for relations with Iraq. She deputised on the Agriculture Committee.\n\nIn the parliament (2014 - 2019), Jill was the Vice-President of the EFA Group, and a member of the Committee on Culture and Education. She deputised on the Transport and Tourism Committee. She was also a member of the Delegation for relations with Switzerland and Norway and to the EU-Iceland Joint Parliamentary Committee and the European Economic Area (EEA) Joint Parliamentary Committee.\n\nJill is former President of Plaid Cymru, and the current Chair of CND Cymru.\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|eu}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of European Parliament]] for [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]]\n  | years  = [[1999 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|1999]]\u2013 2020\n}}\n{{s-non  | reason  = Constituency abolished }}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box | title = Chair of [[Plaid Cymru]] | years = 1994\u20131996 | before = [[John Dixon (Welsh politician)|John Dixon]] | after = [[Marc Phillips]] }}\n{{succession box| title=Vice President of [[Plaid Cymru]] | years=2004\u20132010 | before=[[Dafydd Iwan]] | after=[[Chris Franks]]}}\n{{s-bef  | before = [[Dafydd Iwan]]}}\n{{S-ttl\n  | title  = President of [[Plaid Cymru]]\n  | years  = 2010\u20132013\n}}\n{{s-non|reason  = Position abolished}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Plaid Cymru}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evans, Jill}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Aberystwyth University]]\n[[Category:People from Ystrad]]\n[[Category:Plaid Cymru councillors]]\n[[Category:Plaid Cymru MEPs]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1999\u20132004]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2004\u20132009]]\n[[Category:MEPs for